  "Constraint forces restrict an object's motion to specific paths or surfaces. They adjust in magnitude to maintain the constraint (e.g., normal force prevents penetration).": "",
  "What is the 'superposition principle' for forces?": "",
  "Multiple forces cannot act on the same object simultaneously": "",
  "Forces cancel in pairs due to Newton's third law": "",
  "The largest force determines the motion": "",
  "Forces from different sources add as vectors to produce the net force": "",
  "The superposition principle states that the net force on an object is the vector sum of all individual forces acting on it: F_net = ΣF_i.": "",
  "What is 'static equilibrium'?": "",
  "When an object moves at constant velocity": "",
  "When an object is at rest and both the net force and net torque are zero": "",
  "When an object has no forces acting on it": "",
  "When only gravitational forces act on an object": "",
  "Static equilibrium requires the object to be at rest with both ΣF = 0 (translational equilibrium) and Στ = 0 (rotational equilibrium).": "",
  "What is a 'pseudo-force' or 'fictitious force'?": "",
  "A force that has no reaction partner": "",
  "A force that is too small to measure": "",
  "A force that exists only in non-inertial reference frames to account for the frame's acceleration": "",
  "A theoretical force that has never been observed": "",
  "Pseudo-forces (like the Coriolis force or centrifugal force) appear in non-inertial frames. They are not real forces from interactions but mathematical corrections to make F = ma work in accelerating frames.": "",
